description:
Acrolein (acrylaldehyde or propenal) is a highly electrophilic unsaturated aldehyde primarily used nowadays in chemical synthesis, especially for acrylic polymers, and very rarely as a herbicide or slimicide, one of its former uses. This is a very strong pulmonary as well as skin irritant utilized as a chemical weapon during World War I. Major concern over acrolein toxicity subsequently focused on its role as a decomposition metabolite of the cytostatic agent cyclophosphamide originating in various adverse effects including cystitis. Acrolein is also formed during the combustion of organic materials, and is suspected to play a role in lung cancer due to tobacco smoking. Marked cytotoxicity in which lipid peroxidation via generation of oxygen radicals is considered to be an essential feature, is a hallmark of acrolein toxicity. Direct cytotoxicity to the lung tissue and cells, such as macrophages, is indeed a critical mechanism in acrolein-induced impairment of non specific resistance to microbial pathogens. Whether specific immune functions can also be altered by exposure to acrolein is somewhat controversial.
&nbsp;
There is conclusive evidence that acrolein exposure results in suppressed lung defenses [396]. Acrolein-induced non specific inflammation is by far the leading mechanism. Irritation of the respiratory airways following acute acrolein exposure involves activation of macrophages that release various cytokines including IL-8 and TNFa [397]. Acrolein is dose-dependently cytotoxic to alveolar macrophages as demonstrated by the induction of apoptosis and necrosis [398]. However, effects on human alveolar macrophages in vitro have been observed only at concentrations that alter cell viability [399]. The chemotactic response of human PMNL in vitro was found to be inhibited at concentrations above 100 µM&nbsp;[400] and this inhibition was suggested to be the consequence of a direct toxic effect of acrolein without any influence on PMNL adherence [401]. Phagocytosis of alveolar and peritoneal macrophages assessed by 51Cr-SRBC uptake and various enzyme activities was enhanced in Sprague-Dawley rats exposed to 0.1,1.0 or 3.0 ppm acrolein 6 hours/day, 5 days/week for 3 weeks, but this was not associated with any change in the lung clearance 35S-labeled Klebsiella pneumoniae at any of the concentration tested [402]. This latter finding is in disagreement with the results of several studies in mice. Dose-dependent impairment of the lung clearance of 32P-labeled Staphylococcus aureus was found in Swiss mice exposed to 3 or 6 ppm acrolein for 8 hours, whereas higher concentrations did not induce more severe impairment [403]. In Swiss mice previously infected by the influenza A/PR8/34 virus, staphylococcal lung clearance was nearly abrogated following inhalation of 6 ppm acrolein for 8 hours. A single 3-hour inhalation of 0.1 ppm acrolein affected neither the pulmonary bactericidal activity of CD1 mice against 35S-labelled Klebsiella pneumoniae nor the mortality induced by an aerosol of Streptococcus zooepidermicus, whereas 5 daily inhalations significantly reduced bactericidal activity, but did not affect mortality [169]. Finally, mice exposed to 1-2 ppm acrolein had a significant inhibition of S.aureus and Proteus mirabilis intrapulmonary killing, which was further augmented in mice previously infected by the Sendai virus [405]. However, exposure of Swiss mice to 2.5 ppm acrolein for 4 hours/day for 4 days had no effect on the intrapulmonary killing of S.aureus, P.mirabilis, or Listeria monocytogenes, and pulmonary elimination of influenza A virus [406].
&nbsp;
Although an influence of acrolein on adaptive immunity has been suggested, there is limited evidence to support this view. The single intravenous administration of 100 µmol/kg acrolein to female mice 1 day before sheep red blood cells resulted in a 50% increase in the DTH response measured by footpad swelling. The anti-SRBC PFC response was increased by 88 and 60% after the administration of 30 and 100 µmol/kg acrolein 1 day before sensitization, and the in vitro PFC response was similarly augmented following acrolein exposure in the range of 3x10-7 to 3x10-6 M [407]. As the same results have been previously reported with cyclophosphamide, the conclusion was made that acrolein is the immunopharmacologically active metabolite of cyclophosphamide. In Sprague-Dawley rats, however, the inhalation of 0.1,1.0,or 3.0 ppm of acrolein 6 hours/day, 5 days/week for 3 weeks had no effects on the anti-SRBC PFC response in lung-associated lymph nodes, the lymphocyte proliferation of splenocytes and lung-associated lymph node cells induced by PHA or Salmonella typhimurium, and the mortality induced by experimental L.monocytogenes infection [408]. The only significant findings were local histological changes of the respiratory epithelium. Acrolein did not induce any significant decrease in the anti-SRBC response of murine splenocytes exposed in vitro for 1 hour to 3 or 10 µM of acrolein, whereas a total abolition of the response was noticed with 100 µM, a concentration that severely altered cell viability. Similar findings were observed on the in vitro PWM-induced IgM response of human tonsilar lymphocytes, whereas there was a 30% decrease in PWM-induced proliferation at the concentration of 10 µM that did not affected cell viability [409]. Acrolein induced a concentration-dependent decrease in IL-1&#946; and IL-2 production by human peripheral blood lymphocytes and had a less marked effect on IL-8,GM-CSF, IL-6,IL-10,and IFN-&#947; production. The IC50 for IL-2,TNF-a and GM-CSF was below 2.5 µMol/L, a concentration that did not affect cell viability [410]. 
&nbsp;
Acrolein failed to produce contact sensitization in guinea pigs [411].

Dieldrin is an organochlorine insecticide originally developed as an alternative to DDT. It is similarly characterized by an extremely long persistence. It was once largely used, but is now banned in most of the world. Relatively little information is available on the immunotoxic potential of dieldrin. Immunosuppressive effects have been found at somewhat high doses only with limited relevance to environmental exposure (see Table).
&nbsp;
A few human studies investigated the immunotoxic potential of dieldrin exposure. A study of 101 Japanese infants (mean age = approx. 10 months) with documented exposure to dioxins, PCBs and various organochlorine insecticides including dieldrin evidenced significance changes in lymphocyte subsets, but none in relation with dieldrin [412]. In Inuit infants during the first year of life, otitis media was the most common infection followed by pulmonary infections and a correlation was found between the relative risk of otitis media, but not pulmonary infections and the concentration of dieldrin in breast milk fat. Only minimal changes in immunologic parameters including lower white blood cell count with lower CD4+ T lymphocyte number at 3 months of age and reduced serum IgA levels at 7 and 12 months of age were evidenced, but no statistical correlation with dieldrin exposure was found [413]. Although the possible relation between pesticide exposure and the occurrence of lymphomas is still a controversial issue, no increase in mortality was found in a cohort of 343 workers with high and documented occupational exposure to dieldrin [414]. Similarly negative results have been published [415]. Studies in wildlife species generated somewhat conflicting results. Exposure of the northern leopard frog (Rana pipiens) to 2.1 ng/g body weight (total dose over the 10-week study) resulted in significant suppression of antibody production and delayed-type hypersensitivity [416]. Samples of lymphoid organs including axilary and inguinal lymph nodes, spleen and thymus from a total of 82 Greenland Sea polar bears (Ursus maritimus) were collected for histopathological examination. Contamination to various organochlorine derivatives including PCBs, hexachlorobenzene, DDT, HCH, chlordane and dieldrin was evidenced by analysis of adipose tissue (blubber samples). No significant histopathological anomalies were found in any of the tissues examined and only an increased count of secondary follicles in the spleen of uncertain relevance correlated with dieldrin exposure [417].
&nbsp;
No hypersensitivity reactions induced by dieldrin have so far been reported except for one case of immunoallergic hemolytic anemia in a 52-year-old male [418]. Although he had no documented history of exposure to dieldrin and low dieldrin concentrations in plasma and adipose tissue, the diagnosis was confirmed by the detection of specific anti-dieldrin antibodies. An increased prevalence of antinuclear antibodies was found in a rural population exposed to various insecticides or mixtures of insecticides including dieldrin. However, no specific data on exposure were provided [419].
